[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A chord of a cycle is an edge that does not belong to the cycle, for which both endpoints belong to the cycle.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a graph in which every cycle of four or more vertices has a chord, so the only induced cycles are triangles.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a chordal graph in which every cycle of length six or more has an odd chord.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is not chordal (unless it is a forest); it is a bipartite graph in which every cycle of six or more vertices has a chord, so the only induced cycles are 4-cycles.
