[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is the collection of degrees of all vertices, in sorted order from largest to smallest.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] In a directed graph, one may distinguish the in-degree (number of incoming edges) and out-degree (number of outgoing edges).
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] , the order of the largest clique minor.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The depth of a node in a rooted tree is the number of edges in the path from the root to the node.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For instance, the depth of the root is 0 and the depth of any one of its adjacent nodes is 1.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] That is, it is the maximum of the distances between pairs of vertices in the graph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] If the graph has weights on its edges, then its weighted diameter measures path length by the sum of the edge weights along a path, while the unweighted diameter measures path length by the number of edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For disconnected graphs, definitions vary: the diameter may be defined as infinite, or as the largest diameter of a connected component, or it may be undefined.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is an undirected graph with four vertices and five edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a simple cycle of length two in a directed graph or a multigraph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The tail of a directed edge whose head is the given vertex.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The head of a directed edge whose tail is the given vertex.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is one in which the edges have a distinguished direction, from one vertex to another.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] , a directed edge is again one that has a distinguished direction; directed edges may also be called arcs or arrows.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Two subgraphs are edge disjoint if they share no edges, and vertex disjoint if they share no vertices.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] between any two vertices in a graph is the length of the shortest path having the two vertices as its endpoints.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A domatic partition of a graph is a partition of the vertices into dominating sets.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] of the graph is the maximum number of dominating sets in such a partition.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a set of vertices that includes or is adjacent to every vertex in the graph; not to be confused with a vertex cover, a vertex set that is incident to all edges in the graph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Important special types of dominating sets include independent dominating sets (dominating sets that are also independent sets) and connected dominating sets (dominating sets that induced connected subgraphs).
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A single-vertex dominating set may also be called a universal vertex.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The domination number of a graph is the number of vertices in the smallest dominating set.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] An ear of a graph is a path whose endpoints may coincide but in which otherwise there are no repetitions of vertices or edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a partition of the edges of a graph into a sequence of ears, each of whose endpoints (after the first one) belong to a previous ear and each of whose interior points do not belong to any previous ear.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] An open ear is a simple path (an ear without repeated vertices), and an open ear decomposition is an ear decomposition in which each ear after the first is open; a graph has an open ear decomposition if and only if it is biconnected.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] An ear is odd if it has an odd number of edges, and an odd ear decomposition is an ear decomposition in which each ear is odd; a graph has an odd ear decomposition if and only if it is factor-critical.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The eccentricity of a vertex is the farthest distance from it to any other vertex.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] An edge is (together with vertices) one of the two basic units out of which graphs are constructed.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Each edge has two (or in hypergraphs, more) vertices to which it is attached, called its endpoints.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Edges may be directed or undirected; undirected edges are also called lines and directed edges are also called arcs or arrows.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] , an edge may be represented as the set of its vertices, and in a directed simple graph it may be represented as an ordered pair of its vertices.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] or totally disconnected graph on a given set of vertices is the graph that has no edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] It is sometimes called the empty graph, but this term can also refer to a graph with no vertices.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a topological representation of a graph as a subset of a topological space with each vertex represented as a point, each edge represented as a curve having the endpoints of the edge as endpoints of the curve, and no other intersections between vertices or edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a graph that has such an embedding onto a torus.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] , a graph with no vertices and no edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] of an infinite graph is an equivalence class of rays, where two rays are equivalent if there is a third ray that includes infinitely many vertices from both of them.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] One of the two vertices joined by a given edge, or one of the first or last vertex of a walk, trail or path.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is the problem of counting the graphs in a given class of graphs, as a function of their order.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] More generally, enumeration problems can refer either to problems of counting a certain class of combinatorial objects (such as cliques, independent sets, colorings, or spanning trees), or of algorithmically listing all such objects.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a walk that uses every edge of a graph exactly once.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] An Eulerian circuit (also called an Eulerian cycle or an Euler tour) is a closed walk that uses every edge exactly once.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] An Eulerian graph is a graph that has an Eulerian circuit.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For an undirected graph, this means that the graph is connected and every vertex has even degree.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For a directed graph, this means that the graph is strongly connected and every vertex has in-degree equal to the out-degree.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] In some cases, the connectivity requirement is loosened, and a graph meeting only the degree requirements is called Eulerian.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Divisible by two; for instance, an even cycle is a cycle whose length is even.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a graph whose edge expansion, vertex expansion, or spectral expansion is bounded away from zero.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] of its adjacency matrix and the second-largest eigenvalue.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] , a connected component of the subset of the plane or surface of the embedding that is disjoint from the graph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For an embedding in the plane, all but one face will be bounded; the one exceptional face that extends to infinity is called the outer (or infinite) face.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A factor of a graph is a spanning subgraph: a subgraph that includes all of the vertices of the graph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A graph is finite if it has a finite number of vertices and a finite number of edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Many sources assume that all graphs are finite without explicitly saying so.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A graph is locally finite if each vertex has a finite number of incident edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] An infinite graph is a graph that is not finite: it has infinitely many vertices, infinitely many edges, or both.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a form of logic in which variables represent vertices of a graph, and there exists a binary predicate to test whether two vertices are adjacent.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] To be distinguished from second order logic, in which variables can also represent sets of vertices or edges.
