[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a mapping from the vertex set of one graph to the vertex set of another graph that maps adjacent vertices to adjacent vertices.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] This type of mapping between graphs is the one that is most commonly used in category-theoretic approaches to graph theory.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A proper graph coloring can equivalently be described as a homomorphism to a complete graph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , having any number of endpoints, in contrast to the requirement that edges of graphs have exactly two endpoints.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a generalization of a graph in which each edge (called a hyperedge in this context) may have more than two endpoints.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] This prefix, in combination with a graph property, indicates a graph that does not have the property but such that every subgraph formed by deleting a single vertex does have the property.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is one that does not have a Hamiltonian cycle, but for which every one-vertex deletion produces a Hamiltonian subgraph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , used for graphs which have a property but for which every one-vertex deletion does not.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] in a graph is a vertex-edge pair such that the vertex is an endpoint of the edge.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] (Adjective) The relation between an edge and one of its endpoints.
