[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The intersection of two graphs is their largest common subgraph, the graph formed by the vertices and edges that belong to both graphs.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph whose vertices correspond to sets or geometric objects, with an edge between two vertices exactly when the corresponding two sets or objects have a nonempty intersection.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] (intersection graphs of the maximal cliques of a graph).
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Every graph is an intersection graph for some family of sets, and this family is called an intersection representation of the graph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] An isolated vertex of a graph is a vertex whose degree is zero, that is, a vertex with no incident edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a one-to-one incidence preserving correspondence of the vertices and edges of one graph to the vertices and edges of another graph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Two graphs related in this way are said to be isomorphic.
