[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A multiple adjacency or multiple edge is a set of more than one edge that all have the same endpoints (in the same direction, in the case of directed graphs).
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A graph with multiple edges is often called a multigraph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The multiplicity of an edge is the number of edges in a multiple adjacency.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The multiplicity of a graph is the maximum multiplicity of any of its edges.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is often used (especially in computer science) to denote the number of vertices in a given graph.
