[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A pseudograph is a graph or multigraph that allows self-loops.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A quasi-line graph or locally co-bipartite graph is a graph in which the open neighborhood of every vertex can be partitioned into two cliques.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] They are used in the structure theory of claw-free graphs.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The edges of a quiver are called arrows.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph whose spectral expansion is as large as possible.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A ray, in an infinite graph, is an infinite simple path with exactly one endpoint.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] of a graph are equivalence classes of rays.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , a graph property is recognizable if its truth can be determined from the deck of the graph.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Many graph properties are known to be recognizable.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] If the reconstruction conjecture is true, all graph properties are recognizable.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] In this context, reconstruction is the formation of a graph from its deck.
