[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A split is called a strong split when it is not crossed by any other split.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A split is called nontrivial when both of its sides have more than one vertex.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A graph is called prime when it has no nontrivial splits.
[src:floyd-warshall-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] (sometimes called vertex cleaving) is an elementary graph operation that splits a vertex into two, where these two new vertices are adjacent to the vertices that the original vertex was adjacent to.
